post_text:
Endeavor families. If you are having problems finding good internet, we recommend the following:

If you are exploring high-speed internet options, we recommend using cabletv.com or smartmove.us to find the best internet or cable provider for your area.

Many providers offer families discounted home internet service, if applicable, through Lifeline, a federally subsidized program. Lifeline is a federal program that lowers the monthly cost of internet. Eligible customers can get a discounted rate towards their bill.

Another low-cost internet options for families is EveryoneOn. Service can be found via your zip co.

If none of these options work for you, please let your teacher know.

What does a day of learning look like in a Virtual Select setting?
â€¢ A blend of classroom and independent learning.
â€¢ The virtual classroom teacher sets the weekly schedule and pace.
â€¢ All virtual learning includes real-time small group instruction from the virtual teacher.
â€¢ Assignments posted in Google Classroom to work on independently.
â€¢ Children with an Individualized Education Program (IEP) or Section 504 Plan will have appropriate accommodations provided.
â€¢ Paced so learning milestones are achieved throughout the year.
â€¢ All assignments expected to be turned in on, or before, the posted due date.
â€¢ Assignments tracked and count toward present virtual attendance.
â€¢ All work is to be submitted on time unless excused by illness or other approved circumstances.

Meet Mr. Schook. He says:

Hello! My name is Karl Schook, and I am joining the ECA team as a University of Wisconsin - Madison graduate with a bachelor's degree in political science and as a trial lawyer of twelve years' experience.

I attended Loyola University Chicago School of Law and, until last year, lived in Chicago and practiced civil rights, employment, and insurance law at the state and federal levels throughout the country. In 2016, 2017, 2019, and 2020 the legal community selected me as someone belonging to the top 2.5% of young lawyers in a state for their legal work. I moved to Kalamazoo in 2019 when my wife took a job at Kellogg, and I am using the opportunity to jump intoâ€¦

Welcome Mr. Pennock, new to the Endeavor team as a Teacher in Residence.

Hello, I am Mr. Craig Pennock. I have Five Years, going on Six in early childhood education. I have a BS in University Studies from Western Michigan University. I was born and raised in Battle Creek Michigan. I am married to a wonderful woman and together we have two beautiful kids, a Son who is three and a daughter who is seven months old. I am passionate about education, history and nature.

I am looking forward to working with you all and watching our students grow throughout the 2020-2021 school year. I am excited to be a part of the team and work with everyone.

post_text:
Meet Ms. Breiler, joining the Endeavor team as our art teacher. Welcome Ms. Breiler!

Hello! My name is Ashley Breiler, and I am a recent graduate from the University of Michigan- Flint, having achieved a Bachelor of Science in Visual Arts Education, with a minor in photography.

I have experience teaching K-12 students through working as a certified substitute teacher, volunteer work, and through my student teaching placements at Davison High School and the Flint Cultural Center Academy. I am familiar with the use of many art mediums including various types of painting and drawing, ceramics, woodworking, weaving, printmaking, etc. I also am familiar with both digital and film photography.

In my free time I enjoy spending time with my family and friends in my hometown of New Lothrop, MI, creating my own artwork, taking photographs, and spending time outdoors camping, hiking, and kayaking.

I am familiar with the use of many art mediums including various types of painting and drawing, ceramics, woodworking, weaving, printmaking, etc. I also am familiar with both digital and film photography.

post_text:
We are super excited to welcome back Mrs. Lisa Scovel to the Endeavor team!

"Most of you know who I am since my children have attended Endeavor since the fall of 2009. For those of you who may not know me, my name is Lisa Scovel. I worked at Endeavor as a para in 2017-2018. I left Endeavor in the spring of 2018 to accept a regional manager position with the international student exchange program that I had been a coordinator for since 2014. Unfortunately, due to a change in a law for the State of Michigan, my position was eliminated as of July 2019. It was an interesting time. Here I was 41 and faced with having to decide what I wanted to be when I grew up. I decided I wanted to be back in the schools. For the 2019-2020 school year I worked for Battle Creek Public Schools as a literacy tutor in a 2nd grade classroom. During this time I decided to go back to school and become an elementary teacher through the alternate route to teaching program offered by Michigan Teachers of Tomorrow. I am very excited to begin my teaching career at Endeavor!"

Dear Endeavor Families,

At Endeavor and National Heritage Academies, we have prided ourselves in establishing a school community that embraces the challenge of serving the needs of all students. This includes ensuring our African American students have a school community that is a safe and secure place where they are treated fairly. Like many of you, we have been paying close attention to the protests and demonstrations against the systemic and institutional racism in this country. To be clear, Endeavor does not tolerate racism or injustice of any kind. We believe in equity, diversity, and unity for all.

To our African American families, you are not invisible. We see you, we hear youâ€¦

post_text:
Dear Endeavor Families:

I am excited to share that Michigan has become the first state in the country to gain federal approval of a program that will provide nutritious food to children who were affected by school closings due to COVID-19.

The Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer Program (P-EBT) provides temporary funding to address emergency food needs and avert financial hardship for families affected by the pandemic. Those already receiving Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP) benefits will see benefits added to their card.

Families can use their pre-loaded EBT card at any retailer that accepts SNAP EBT benefits. You can find a list of retailers on the SNAP Retailers website.

text:
April 6, 2020

Dear National Heritage Academies Families:

During these times of uncertainty, leaders throughout National Heritage Academies (NHA) are committed to ensuring our students continue on their track to academic excellence. Though many things have been different the past several weeks, we are continuing to offer the opportunity for students to apply for an NHA CollegeBoundâ„¢ Scholarship.

post_text:
Young Five Kindergarten
Children enter school with a variety of experiences. We offer options to meet their individual needs. Younger learners who turn 5 between September 1 and December 1 may consider our Young 5 program. All students, including those in Young 5 kindergarten, must be five years old on or before December 1st.

We created Young 5 to support younger learners who may benefit from a transitional year. Children adjust to the social and academic demands of school in a fun, hands-on environment. Young 5 provides â€˜the gift of timeâ€™ so younger learners can succeed in Kindergarten. Teachers help them develop social, motor and academic skills necessary to prosper in a regular kindergarten class. Students who complete their first year in the Young 5 program will be promoted to the regular kindergarten program the following year.

Apply today at www.endeavorcharteracademy.org

post_text: Come join us as we turn down the volume of everyday life and focus on new ways to strengthen our families. These workshops cover a variety of topics including parenting styles, effective discipline strategies, health and nutrition, and self-care. Remember...if you regenerate your thinking, you can regenerate your LIFE. This is limited to the first 25 families to sign up. It is a 5 part series every Thursday, beginning Thursday January 30th and ending on February 27th. Please plan on attending at least 4 out of 5 sessions if you cannot attend them all. Doors open at 5:15 with a light dinner and the discussion is 5:30-7:00. Childcare is available as well! Please RSVP to this event by emailing Mrs. Nye at 14.lnye@nhaschools.com. Deadline to sign up is tomorrow!

post_text:
Please help the less fortunate in our community stay warm this winter by donating a new pair of socks! People generally think of coats, hats, scarves, gloves, and boots as donation items for the colder months, but rarely do they think of socks.

In order to help secure this overlooked, but highly needed item, Endeavorâ€™s Soaring Eagles Chapter of the National Junior Honor Society is hosting a school wide Sock Drive. Adult sizes are needed the most, but child sizes are also welcome. All socks will be donated to local homeless shelters/organizations.

The Sock Drive through Thursday, December 19th. Socks may be dropped off in your childâ€™s classroom. The class in each wing that brings in the greatest number of new pairs of socks will earn an ice cream party!!!!!

Thank you in advance for your help and support,

post_text: Endeavor's holiday shop will return for the holiday season! The flyer and money envelope is in your child's folder this week. Please review the flyer for detailed information. The majority of the gifts are $1.00-$6.00. It is extremely helpful if you send cash in the envelope (on their assigned day)and mark on the outside of the envelope who the students are purchasing for.

Nov. 11, 2019
Dear Endeavor Charter Academy Families:
As we approach winter, I am writing to share details on our inclement weather policies and
procedures. Our goal is to provide our students with a quality education and to do so the school
needs to be open. However, the safety of our students and staff is a top priority, and we recognize
at times, closing the school is in everyoneâ€™s best interest.
Leadership does not take the decision to close lightly. We take into consideration road conditions,
temperature, and what local school districts are doing. Remember, families that attend Endeavor
Charter Academy come from across our community.
If we experience a school closing, we will notify allâ€¦ More

post_text: Starting tomorrow, Helmer Road will be closed to thru-traffic at the railroad tracks.Access will be maintained to the school at both driveways. While these changes will look a little different than what we are used to, we anticipate the flow through the drop-off and pick-up line will remain a smooth process. We thank you, in advance, for your patience.
